### Prime Minister of the United Kingdom

The [Prime Minister of the United Kingdom](/Prime_Minister_of_the_United_Kingdom) is the head of government of the [United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland](/United_Kingdom). The prime minister is not directly elected by the people; instead, they are almost always the leader of the [political party](/political_party) that commands a majority in the [House of Commons](/House_of_Commons), the lower house of the [Parliament of the United Kingdom](/Parliament_of_the_United_Kingdom). The prime minister is appointed by the [Sovereign](/Sovereign) (currently [King Charles III](/King_Charles_III)), who is the head of state.

This position, while holding significant power, is not codified in a single document but rather evolved through centuries of [constitutional practice](/constitutional_practice) and [convention](/convention_(rule_of_law)). The prime minister is typically a [Member of Parliament](/Member_of_Parliament) (MP) and must maintain the confidence of the House of Commons to remain in office. If a prime minister loses a vote of no confidence, they are expected to resign, or the Sovereign may dissolve Parliament and call a [general election](/general_election).

The office of prime minister has its origins in the [18th century](/18th_century), evolving from the role of the [First Lord of the Treasury](/First_Lord_of_the_Treasury), who began to preside over meetings of the [Cabinet](/Cabinet_(government_of_the_United_Kingdom)). The term "Prime Minister" itself was initially used pejoratively, implying someone who wielded undue influence, but it eventually became the accepted title for the head of government.

#### Powers and Responsibilities

The prime minister is the chief political adviser to the Sovereign and holds considerable influence over [domestic policy](/domestic_policy) and [foreign policy](/foreign_policy). Key responsibilities include:

*   **Appointing and dismissing ministers:** The prime minister selects the members of the [Cabinet](/Cabinet_(government_of_the_United_Kingdom)) and other ministers, forming the government. They have the authority to dismiss ministers, reshuffling the government as they see fit.
*   **Chairing the Cabinet:** The prime minister presides over Cabinet meetings, setting the agenda and guiding discussions. The Cabinet is the supreme decision-making body of the government, responsible for formulating policy.
*   **Leading the country in Parliament:** The prime minister is the principal spokesperson for the government in the House of Commons, answering questions, introducing legislation, and defending government policy.
*   **Representing the UK internationally:** The prime minister represents the United Kingdom at international summits and negotiations, such as meetings of the [G7](/G7), [G20](/G20), and the [United Nations General Assembly](/United_Nations_General_Assembly).
*   **Commander-in-Chief:** While the Sovereign is the nominal commander-in-chief of the [British Armed Forces](/British_Armed_Forces), the prime minister exercises practical control over military operations and defence policy.
*   **Recommending appointments:** The prime minister advises the Sovereign on a wide range of appointments, including [judges](/judges), [senior civil servants](/senior_civil_servants), and [church appointments](/church_appointments).
*   **Dissolving Parliament:** The prime minister has the power to advise the Sovereign to dissolve Parliament and call a general election, although this power has been subject to [parliamentary reform](/parliamentary_reform).

#### Evolution of the Office

The role of the prime minister developed gradually, without a formal act of [parliamentary creation](/parliamentary_creation). Early precedents can be traced back to the [17th century](/17th_century), but it was in the [18th century](/18th_century) that the office began to take shape. [Robert Walpole](/Robert_Walpole) is often considered the first *de facto* prime minister, holding significant influence during the reign of [King George I](/King_George_I) and [King George II](/King_George_II). His premiership, lasting over two decades, established many of the conventions associated with the role.

The [19th century](/19th_century) saw the further consolidation of the prime minister's power, particularly with the rise of the [two-party system](/two-party_system) and the increasing dominance of the House of Commons. Figures like [William Gladstone](/William_Gladstone) and [Benjamin Disraeli](/Benjamin_Disraeli) became powerful leaders who shaped national policy and the direction of their respective parties, the [Liberal Party](/Liberal_Party) and the [Conservative Party](/Conservative_Party).

The [20th century](/20th_century) witnessed further formalisation, with the establishment of the [Cabinet Office](/Cabinet_Office) and the formalisation of the prime minister's salary and residence at [10 Downing Street](/10_Downing_Street). The immense pressures of two [World Wars](/World_War) also amplified the prime minister's role as a wartime leader. Post-war, the office continued to evolve, grappling with [decolonisation](/decolonisation), [economic challenges](/economic_challenges), and changing social landscapes.

#### Appointment and Tenure

The prime minister is appointed by the Sovereign. This appointment is not arbitrary; the Sovereign acts on the convention that they must invite the individual most likely to command the confidence of the House of Commons to form a government. This is typically the leader of the party that has won a majority of seats in a general election. If no single party has a majority, the Sovereign will seek to identify a leader who can command the support of a coalition or minority government.

The tenure of a prime minister is not fixed. They remain in office as long as they retain the confidence of the House of Commons and the leader of their party. A prime minister may resign for various reasons, including:

*   Losing a [vote of no confidence](/vote_of_no_confidence) in the House of Commons.
*   Losing the leadership of their political party.
*   Deciding to step down after a period in office.
*   Being unable to form a government after a general election.

#### Residences and Symbols

The official residence and principal workplace of the prime minister is [10 Downing Street](/10_Downing_Street) in [Westminster](/Westminster), [London](/London). This historic building has been the customary home of the prime minister since the [1730s](/1730s). The prime minister also has a country house, [Chequers](/Chequers), in [Buckinghamshire](/Buckinghamshire), which serves as a place for informal meetings and relaxation.

The prime minister's insignia are less formal than those of the Sovereign, but the role is symbolically represented by the [Mace](/Mace) in the House of Commons and the [Prime Minister's Questions](/Prime_Minister's_Questions) session, where the prime minister is directly accountable to Parliament.

#### Current and Historical Prime Ministers

The list of prime ministers is extensive, spanning centuries of British political history. From [Walpole](/Robert_Walpole) to the current incumbent, each prime minister has left their mark on the nation's trajectory. Notable figures include [Winston Churchill](/Winston_Churchill), who led the country through [World War II](/World_War_II); [Clement Attlee](/Clement_Attlee), who oversaw the creation of the [National Health Service](/National_Health_Service); and [Margaret Thatcher](/Margaret_Thatcher), whose [economic reforms](/economic_reforms) profoundly reshaped British society. Understanding their legacies is crucial to grasping the evolution of the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom).

